
Level 1 : HTML : 
1.What are the new features in HTML5? Like : <article>, <section>, <canvas> ,etc .
2.What is the difference between a block-level and an inline element?

Ans:- Block-Level Element: Starts on a new line and takes up the full width available.
           Examples: <div>, <p>, <h1>, <ul>, <ol>, <li>, <header>, <footer>, <section>

Usage: Block-level elements are typically used for larger structures of a webpage, like sections of 
content, headers, paragraphs, and lists.

Inline Element: Does not start on a new line and only takes up as much width as its content. 
           Examples: <span>, <a>, <strong>, <em>, <img>, <b>, <i>

Usage: Inline elements are used to format parts of content within block-level elements,
such as applying styles to specific text within a paragraph or linking text.

3.What is the purpose of the <!DOCTYPE> declaration?

Ans:- All HTML documents must start with a <!DOCTYPE> declaration.
The declaration is not an HTML tag. It is an "information" to the browser about what document type to expect.

4.What is the difference between <div> and <span>?

Ans:- The <div> and <span> elements in HTML serve different purposes and have distinct characteristics:
1.<div>
Type: Block-level element
Display: Takes up the full width of its container and starts on a new line.
Usage: Used for grouping and organizing larger sections of content, such as layout sections, containers, and groups of elements.
Exmaple:- <div>
  <h1>Welcome</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph inside a div.</p>
</div>
2.<span>
Type: Inline element
Display: Only takes up as much width as its content and does not start on a new line.
Usage: Used for styling or applying attributes to a small portion of text or a small element within a block-level element.

Example:- <p>This is a <span style="color: red;">highlighted</span> word in a paragraph.</p>

5.How do you create a hyperlink in HTML?

Ans:- To create a hyperlink in HTML, you use the <a> (anchor) tag. 
            <a href="URL">Link Text</a>
*href: This attribute specifies the URL or the destination of the hyperlink.
*Link Text: This is the text that will be clickable in the browser.

*****Summary
1.Use the <a> tag with the href attribute to create hyperlinks.
2.Add target="_blank" to open links in a new tab.
3.Use mailto: for email links.
4.Use # followed by an id to link to specific sections on the same page.

